isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.52) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.03. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (S.E. = 0.25, p < .001, 95% CI [13.03, 14.03]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 0.36, p = 0.721, 95% CI [-0.83, 0.58]; Std. beta = -0.04, 95% CI [-0.24, 0.17])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.71, S.E. = 0.98, p = 0.474, 95% CI [-2.64, 1.22]; Std. beta = -0.20, 95% CI [-0.76, 0.35])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.99, S.E. = 1.33, p = 0.025, 95% CI [-5.59, -0.38]; Std. beta = -0.86, 95% CI [-1.61, -0.11])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
